  "prompt": "How far in space have we reached in light years, and what have we found till there?",
  "response": "As of now, human spacecraft have not traveled beyond our solar system. The Voyager 1, launched by NASA in 1977, is the farthest spacecraft from Earth; it entered interstellar space in August 2012 and is currently more than 14 billion miles (approximately 21 billion kilometers) away from Earth. This distance translates to roughly 0.0022 light years.\n\nWhen it comes to observations, astronomers using telescopes have been able to see much further into the universe. The Hubble Space Telescope and various ground-based observatories have detected objects billions of light years away. For example, the most distant galaxy confirmed so far is GN-z11, which is about 13.4 billion light years away.\n\nFrom our observations, we have learned about the existence of various celestial phenomena such as:\n- Exoplanets orbiting other stars, some of which may have conditions suitable for life.\n- The structures of galaxies, including their formation and evolution.\n- The presence of black holes, neutron stars, and other exotic objects.\n- The cosmic microwave background radiation, which gives us insight into the early universe.\n- Observations of supernovae and other stellar events that inform us about the life cycles of stars.\n\nThese observations help deepen our understanding of the universe and its vastness, although physically traveling to these distances is currently far beyond our technological capabilities.",
